  1. Get a frequency breakdown of the number of chicks, their average weight and the standard deviation of the weights in each of the diets at the start of the study. Store the resulting data frame in a variable named weight0 and print.

weight0 = cw %>% 
      filter(Time == 0) %>% 
      group_by(Diet) %>%
      summarize(Average=mean(weight), Deviation=sd(weight))

  3. In the complete data set introduce a new variable that measures the current weight difference compared to day 0. Name this variable weightgain and print the first 3 rows of the new data frame.

    weight_init = cw %>% filter(Time == 0) %>% arrange(Chick)
cw = cw %>%
     mutate(weightgain = weight - weight_init[Chick, "weight"])

  5. Answer each of the following questions using numerical and graphical summary. Also explain what you found: (a) Which chick gained the most weight and which gained the least weight? (b) What diets were they on?

    Part a:

    To see which chicks have the most extreme weights we can simply call the corresponding methods for each:

    mx = max(cw$weightgain)
mn = min(cw$weightgain)

print(cat("Max weight gain is:", mx, fill=TRUE))
    ## Max weight gain is: 332
## NULL
    print(cat("Min weight gain is:", mn, fill=TRUE))
    ## Min weight gain is: -4
## NULL

    As we can see here, the chick that gained the most weight gained 332, and the chick that gained the least amount of weight, actually lost 4. To see which chicks they are, we can use select

    extremes = cw %>% filter(weightgain == mx | weightgain == mn)
print(extremes)
    ##   weight Time Chick Diet weightgain
## 1     39    2     3    1         -4
## 2     35    2    18    1         -4
## 3    373   21    35    3        332

    And now we can see that the chicks that lost weight are chicks 3, and 18, and the chick that gained the most weight is chick 35.

  8. What else do you find interesting in the dataset? Show your exploratory analysis.

    An interesting question that could be asked is, Is there a correlation between incomplete data sets, and which diet the chick was eating? Assuming that an incomplete data line most likely means that the chick died during the experiment, it raises a good question of whether maybe the diet had something to do with it.

    incomplete = cw %>% filter(!(Chick %in% complete$Chick)) %>% group_by(Diet)
ggplot(incomplete, aes(x=Time, y=weight, color=Chick)) + geom_point()

    After looking at how many chicks dont have complete data, Im going to guess that this might be a bit of a bad sample, but lets continue anyway; With a bar chart, I can easily see the percentage in each diet.

    ggplot(incomplete, aes(x=Diet, fill=Chick)) + geom_bar()

    From this graph, you can see that roughly 80% of the chicks that didnt have complete data entries, were from diet 1, and only one entry was from diet 4, thats actually kind of suspicious, but could have several reasons.

    • Diet 1 kills the chicks more often than any other diet (the obvious one)
    • The experiment was a linear process meaning that most mistakes would be made early one during initial stages (diet 1)
    • The experimenters hadnt dealt with chicks before and thus might have killed a few in the beginning from negligence
    • It was just a bad batch of chicks
    • It was an illness

    But one other thing to notice here is that three of the chicks are almost completely consecutive, which points to an illness, spreading amongst nearby chicks in the containment area. In fact Id be confident to say that whatever caused chicks 18, 16, and 15, to not complete their entries was likely the same thing, whether that be a mistake made a by a person, an illness, maybe an animal, who knows.

    This was really cool, I didnt expect to find anything when I looked for the absence of information instead of presence of information.
